[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/connectors/sdk#usage-notes","content":"Field mappings allow you to rename fields during format conversion"},"532":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sdk-40","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/connectors/sdk#usage-notes","content":"Protocol Buffers provide efficient binary serialization compared to JSON"},"533":{"id":"/docs/faq/faq","page_id":"/docs/faq/faq","type":"page","content":"FAQ","breadcrumbs":["Documentation","FAQ"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/faq/faq"},"534":{"id":"/docs/faq/faq-0","page_id":"/docs/faq/faq","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/faq/faq#q-what-is-the-difference-between-iggy-and-traditional-message-brokers-like-kafka","content":"Q: What is the difference between Iggy and traditional message brokers like Kafka?"},"535":{"id":"/docs/faq/faq-1","page_id":"/docs/faq/faq","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/faq/faq#q-are-there-plans-to-support-kafka-protocol-in-iggy","content":"Q: Are there plans to support Kafka protocol in Iggy?"},"536":{"id":"/docs/faq/faq-2","page_id":"/docs/faq/faq","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/faq/faq#q-what-transport-protocol-should-i-use","content":"Q: What transport protocol should I use?"},"537":{"id":"/docs/faq/faq-3","page_id":"/docs/faq/faq","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/faq/faq#q-what-are-the-system-requirements","content":"Q: What are the system requirements?"},"538":{"id":"/docs/faq/faq-4","page_id":"/docs/faq/faq","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/faq/faq#q-how-does-consumer-group-rebalancing-work","content":"Q: How does consumer group rebalancing work?"},"539":{"id":"/docs/faq/faq-5","page_id":"/docs/faq/faq","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/faq/faq#q-does-iggy-support-exactly-once-delivery","content":"Q: Does Iggy support exactly-once delivery?"},"540":{"id":"/docs/faq/faq-6","page_id":"/docs/faq/faq","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/faq/faq#q-how-do-i-secure-my-iggy-deployment","content":"Q: How do I secure my Iggy deployment?"},"541":{"id":"/docs/faq/faq-7","page_id":"/docs/faq/faq","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/faq/faq#q-can-i-use-iggy-with-my-existing-tooling","content":"Q: Can I use Iggy with my existing tooling?"},"542":{"id":"/docs/faq/faq-8","page_id":"/docs/faq/faq","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/faq/faq#q-what-happened-to-the-tokio-based-runtime","content":"Q: What happened to the Tokio-based runtime?"},"543":{"id":"/docs/faq/faq-9","page_id":"/docs/faq/faq","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/faq/faq#q-is-clusteringreplication-available","content":"Q: Is clustering/replication available?"},"544":{"id":"/docs/faq/faq-10","page_id":"/docs/faq/faq","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/faq/faq#q-what-examples-are-available","content":"Q: What examples are available?"},"545":{"id":"/docs/faq/faq-11","page_id":"/docs/faq/faq","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/faq/faq#q-what-is-the-difference-between-iggy-and-traditional-message-brokers-like-kafka","content":"Iggy is a persistent message streaming platform that stores messages in an append-only log format, similar to Kafka. However, Iggy is designed for high performance and low latency using io_uring and a thread-per-core architecture. Iggy doesn't use kafka protocol, instead it has its own binary protocol optimized for speed and efficiency, which means that clients need to use our native client libraries."},"546":{"id":"/docs/faq/faq-12","page_id":"/docs/faq/faq","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/faq/faq#q-are-there-plans-to-support-kafka-protocol-in-iggy","content":"Currently, Iggy does not support the Kafka protocol. Our focus is on providing a high-performance native protocol that leverages the strengths of Iggy's architecture. However, we are open to community contributions (in fact there is an discussion about it)."},"547":{"id":"/docs/faq/faq-13","page_id":"/docs/faq/faq","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/faq/faq#q-what-transport-protocol-should-i-use","content":"For maximum throughput and lowest latency, use TCP. If you need built-in encryption without configuring TLS separately, QUIC is a good choice. WebSocket works well for browser-based clients. HTTP is the most accessible but has the highest overhead due to JSON serialization and stateless connections (no consumer groups)."},"548":{"id":"/docs/faq/faq-14","page_id":"/docs/faq/faq","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/faq/faq#q-what-are-the-system-requirements","content":"Iggy is a single binary with no external dependencies. On Linux, it uses io_uring for maximum performance, which requires kernel 5.19+. The server starts with around 20 MB of RAM (plus the configured memory pool, default 4 GiB). For Docker, you need to set SYS_NICE capability, disable seccomp, and set unlimited memlock."},"549":{"id":"/docs/faq/faq-15","page_id":"/docs/faq/faq","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/faq/faq#q-how-does-consumer-group-rebalancing-work","content":"When consumers join or leave a consumer group, the server triggers cooperative partition rebalancing. Partitions are redistributed among active members. During rebalancing, there is a pending revocation phase (configurable timeout, default 30s) to ensure in-progress message processing can complete before partitions move to new owners."},"550":{"id":"/docs/faq/faq-16","page_id":"/docs/faq/faq","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/faq/faq#q-does-iggy-support-exactly-once-delivery","content":"Iggy supports at-most-once (with auto-commit), at-least-once (without auto-commit, manual offset management), and exactly-once via application-level deduplication. The server provides optional hash-based message deduplication per partition to help with this."},"551":{"id":"/docs/faq/faq-17","page_id":"/docs/faq/faq","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/faq/faq#q-how-do-i-secure-my-iggy-deployment","content":"Iggy supports TLS on all transport protocols, Argon2id password hashing, granular per-stream/per-topic permissions, Personal Access Tokens for programmatic access, and optional AES-256-GCM encryption at rest. For the HTTP API, JWT tokens are used for session management. See the Security documentation for details."},"552":{"id":"/docs/faq/faq-18","page_id":"/docs/faq/faq","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/faq/faq#q-can-i-use-iggy-with-my-existing-tooling","content":"Iggy provides a Model Context Protocol (MCP) server with 40+ tools for LLM integration, connectors for piping data to/from external systems (PostgreSQL, MongoDB, Elasticsearch, Apache Iceberg, Quickwit), Prometheus metrics, and OpenTelemetry traces/logs. The HTTP API works with any REST client."},"553":{"id":"/docs/faq/faq-19","page_id":"/docs/faq/faq","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/faq/faq#q-what-happened-to-the-tokio-based-runtime","content":"Iggy migrated from Tokio to a thread-per-core architecture with compio (which uses io_uring on Linux) starting with version 0.6.0. The migration delivered major performance improvements, including up to 92% better P9999 tail latency and 18% throughput improvement with fsync enabled. You can read the full story in the thread-per-core io_uring blog post."},"554":{"id":"/docs/faq/faq-20","page_id":"/docs/faq/faq","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/faq/faq#q-is-clusteringreplication-available","content":"Clustering based on Viewstamped Replication (VSR) is under active development. The core consensus protocol, view change mechanism, deterministic timeout management, and network simulator are implemented. It is not yet production-ready. See the Clustering documentation for the current state."},"555":{"id":"/docs/faq/faq-21","page_id":"/docs/faq/faq","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/faq/faq#q-what-examples-are-available","content":"Examples are available in the repository for multiple languages: Rust (basic, getting-started, message headers, compression, multi-tenant, stream builder, TLS), Go, Python, Java, Node.js, and C#. Docker Compose files and Helm charts are also provided."},"556":{"id":"/docs/sdk/introduction","page_id":"/docs/sdk/introduction","type":"page","content":"Introduction","breadcrumbs":["Documentation","SDK"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/sdk/introduction"},"557":{"id":"/docs/sdk/introduction-0","page_id":"/docs/sdk/introduction","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/sdk/introduction#connection-string","content":"Connection string"},"558":{"id":"/docs/sdk/introduction-1","page_id":"/docs/sdk/introduction","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/sdk/introduction#common-operations","content":"Common operations"},"559":{"id":"/docs/sdk/introduction-2","page_id":"/docs/sdk/introduction","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/sdk/introduction#polling-strategies","content":"Polling strategies"},"560":{"id":"/docs/sdk/introduction-3","page_id":"/docs/sdk/introduction","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/sdk/introduction#partitioning-strategies","content":"Partitioning strategies"},"561":{"id":"/docs/sdk/introduction-4","page_id":"/docs/sdk/introduction","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/introduction","content":"Iggy provides official client SDKs in multiple languages. The Rust SDK is the most feature-complete, offering both a high-level API (with auto-batching, consumer groups, offset management, retry logic) and a low-level API for direct protocol operations."},"562":{"id":"/docs/sdk/introduction-5","page_id":"/docs/sdk/introduction","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/introduction","content":"Language"},"563":{"id":"/docs/sdk/introduction-6","page_id":"/docs/sdk/introduction","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/introduction","content":"Package"},"564":{"id":"/docs/sdk/introduction-7","page_id":"/docs/sdk/introduction","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/introduction","content":"Registry"},"565":{"id":"/docs/sdk/introduction-8","page_id":"/docs/sdk/introduction","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/introduction","content":"Transport"},"566":{"id":"/docs/sdk/introduction-9","page_id":"/docs/sdk/introduction","tags":[],"type":"text","url