,"content":"Length of payload"},"1246":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-55","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#message-binary-format","content":"reserved"},"1247":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-56","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#message-binary-format","content":"56..64"},"1248":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-57","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#message-binary-format","content":"u64"},"1249":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-58","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#message-binary-format","content":"Reserved, must be 0"},"1250":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-59","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#message-binary-format","content":"After the 64-byte header: user_headers (variable, length from user_headers_length) followed by payload (variable, length from payload_length)."},"1251":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-60","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#message-binary-format","content":"All fields are stored in little-endian byte order. The header is exactly 64 bytes, which allows for efficient aligned reads. Messages are stored contiguously in the .log file with no padding between them."},"1252":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-61","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#indexes","content":"Each segment has an accompanying .index file that stores positional and time indexes. These allow the server to quickly locate messages by offset or timestamp without scanning the entire log file."},"1253":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-62","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#indexes","content":"Index caching can be configured via the cache_indexes setting:"},"1254":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-63","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#indexes","content":"Strategy"},"1255":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-64","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#indexes","content":"Behavior"},"1256":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-65","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#indexes","content":"\"all\""},"1257":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-66","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#indexes","content":"All segment indexes loaded at startup, kept in memory"},"1258":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-67","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#indexes","content":"\"open_segment\""},"1259":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-68","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#indexes","content":"Only the active segment's indexes are cached (default)"},"1260":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-69","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#indexes","content":"\"none\""},"1261":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-70","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#indexes","content":"Indexes are loaded on-demand from disk"},"1262":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-71","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#indexes","content":"If an index file becomes corrupted or goes missing, the IndexRebuilder can reconstruct it by scanning the corresponding .log file and parsing message headers."},"1263":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-72","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#write-pipeline","content":"Messages flow through a multi-stage pipeline before reaching disk:"},"1264":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-73","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#write-pipeline","content":"The MessagesWriter uses vectored I/O (writev) with MAX_IOV_COUNT=1024 to batch multiple message buffers into a single syscall, which significantly reduces the overhead of writing many small messages."},"1265":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-74","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#write-pipeline","content":"The flush thresholds are configurable:"},"1266":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-75","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#write-pipeline","content":"messages_required_to_save (default 1024, minimum 1) - count threshold"},"1267":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-76","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#write-pipeline","content":"size_of_messages_required_to_save (default \"1 MiB\") - size threshold"},"1268":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-77","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#write-pipeline","content":"These are soft limits - the actual count/size may be higher depending on the last batch size."},"1269":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-78","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#memory-pool","content":"Iggy includes a custom memory pool to eliminate allocation overhead on the hot path. The pool has 32 buckets with buffer sizes ranging from 256 B up to 512 MiB (with non-uniform spacing optimized for common message sizes). When a component needs a buffer, it requests one from the appropriate bucket. When done, the buffer is returned to the pool."},"1270":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-79","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#memory-pool","content":"This avoids frequent heap allocations during message processing and enables zero-copy message passing between internal components."},"1271":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-80","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#zero-copy-deserialization","content":"Iggy uses a custom zero-copy deserialization approach for reading messages. Instead of fully deserializing each message from disk, the system maintains a separate index vector of u32 values pointing to positions within the raw message data buffer. When a consumer polls messages, the server yields views into the underlying buffer rather than copying data, and performs just-in-time deserialization only for the fields the consumer actually needs."},"1272":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-81","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#zero-copy-deserialization","content":"This approach delivered significant performance improvements:"},"1273":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-82","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#zero-copy-deserialization","content":"Producer throughput: +40% (1.7 to 2.4 GB/s)"},"1274":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-83","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#zero-copy-deserialization","content":"Consumer throughput: +90% (2.1 to 4.0 GB/s)"},"1275":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-84","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#zero-copy-deserialization","content":"Producer P99 latency: +63% improvement (4.23 to 2.59ms)"},"1276":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-85","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#zero-copy-deserialization","content":"Consumer P99 latency: +50% improvement (2.93 to 1.46ms)"},"1277":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-86","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#retention-and-cleanup","content":"Iggy supports two independent retention policies for automatic message cleanup, both configurable per topic:"},"1278":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-87","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#retention-and-cleanup","content":"Size-based retention: when a topic exceeds max_size, the oldest sealed segments are removed to make room. Deletion kicks in at 90% of the limit. The active segment is always protected."},"1279":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-88","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#retention-and-cleanup","content":"Time-based retention: segments with all messages older than message_expiry are deleted. The cleaner runs at a configurable interval (default 1 minute) when cleaner_enabled is true."},"1280":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-89","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#retention-and-cleanup","content":"Both policies can be active simultaneously and only affect sealed segments. The active segment is never deleted, even if its messages have expired."},"1281":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-90","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#message-deduplication","content":"Optional server-side deduplication can be enabled per partition. When active, a hash-based MessageDeduplicator keeps track of recently seen message IDs and silently drops duplicates. This is useful for achieving exactly-once semantics at the application level."},"1282":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-91","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#encryption","content":"Iggy supports optional AES-256-GCM encryption for message payloads and state commands. When enabled, messages are encrypted before being written to disk and decrypted when read. The encryption key is a 32-byte base64-encoded string."},"1283":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-92","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#compression","content":"Topic-level compression is supported with the following algorithms: none, gzip, lz4, zstd. The allow_override setting controls whether individual topics can override the default algorithm."},"1284":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-93","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#backup-and-archiving","content":"Sealed segments can be archived to local/NAS storage or S3-compatible cloud storage (AWS S3, MinIO). Since sealed segments are immutable, they are safe to copy in parallel without any coordination. The archive path is configurable under system.backup.path."},"1285":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-94","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#state-persistence-write-ahead-log","content":"All metadata operations (create stream, delete topic, create user, etc.) are persisted to a write-ahead log (state.messages). Each entry contains:"},"1286":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-95","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#state-persistence-write-ahead-log","content":"Field"},"1287":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-96","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#state-persistence-write-ahead-log","content":"Size"},"1288":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-97","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#state-persistence-write-ahead-log","content":"Description"},"1289":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-98","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#state-persistence-write-ahead-log","content":"index"},"1290":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-99","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#state-persistence-write-ahead-log","content":"8 bytes"},"1291":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-100","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#state-persistence-write-ahead-log","content":"Sequential entry number"},"1292":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-101","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#state-persistence-write-ahead-log","content":"term"},"1293":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-102","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#state-persistence-write-ahead-log","content":"8 bytes"},"1294":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-103","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#state-persistence-write-ahead-log","content":"VSR consensus term"},"1295":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-104","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#state-persistence-write-ahead-log","content":"timestamp"},"1296":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-105","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#state-persistence-write-ahead-log","content":"8 bytes"},"1297":{"id":"/docs/server/storage-engine-106","page_id":"/docs/server/storage-engine","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/storage-engine#state-persistence-write-ahead-log","content":"Entry timestamp"},"1298":{"id":"/docs/server/storag