ussed in the dedicated guide."},"1940":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/examples-4","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/examples","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/examples","content":"Stream builder - examples using the IggyStream, IggyStreamProducer, and IggyStreamConsumer builder APIs as discussed in the stream builder guide."},"1941":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/examples-5","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/examples","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/examples","content":"Message envelope - the example of how to send a message with a custom envelope e.g. to differentiate between different types of messages."},"1942":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/examples-6","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/examples","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/examples","content":"Message headers - the example of how to send a message with custom headers (typed headers, message type discrimination, client-side compression)."},"1943":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/examples-7","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/examples","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/examples","content":"Multi-tenant - the comprehensive example of how to structure your application to support multiple tenants (separated by the unique streams) with the different users, permissions, topics etc."},"1944":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/examples-8","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/examples","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/examples","content":"TCP TLS - TLS-encrypted TCP connections with custom CA certificates."},"1945":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/examples-9","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/examples","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/examples","content":"Sink data producer - generating random JSON records in bulk batches for sink connector testing."},"1946":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","type":"page","content":"High-level SDK","breadcrumbs":["Documentation","SDK","Rust"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk"},"1947":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-0","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"Connection string"},"1948":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-1","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#producer","content":"Producer"},"1949":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-2","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#consumer","content":"Consumer"},"1950":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-3","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","content":"If you've read through the getting started guide, you might have noticed that it's quite verbose and requires a lot of boilerplate code to get started. This is where the High-level SDK comes in, as it does provide a more user-friendly interface to interact with the Iggy API for both, producer and consumer. Let's consider the following features:"},"1951":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-4","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","content":"Automatically creating & joining the consumer groups"},"1952":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-5","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","content":"Committing the offset depending on the particular mode (e.g. in the background based on some interval, after polling N messages etc.)"},"1953":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-6","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","content":"Batching the messages, whether it's about producing or consuming"},"1954":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-7","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","content":"Processing the messages as if the stream was an async iterator"},"1955":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-8","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","content":"Reusing the same client for both, producing and consuming on the same topic without repeating the configuration"},"1956":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-9","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","content":"And more..."},"1957":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-10","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"Instead of providing the configuration for the client, you can use the connection string. It's a string that contains all the necessary information to connect to the Iggy API with only a single caveat, as it does support TCP protocol only for now. Here's the basic example:"},"1958":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-11","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"Which can be used to create the client like this:"},"1959":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-12","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"By default, the connection string will use TCP transport protocol, but you can also specify the other one by including +{protocol} to the initial iggy part, for example:"},"1960":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-13","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"And here's the full example of TCP connection string with its all optional parts:"},"1961":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-14","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"By default, the TCP connection string is parsed with the following options:"},"1962":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-15","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"tls - whether to use the TLS connection or not (default: false)"},"1963":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-16","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"tls_domain - the domain to use for the TLS connection (default: None)"},"1964":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-17","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"tls_ca_file - the path to the CA file to use for the TLS connection (default: None)"},"1965":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-18","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"reconnection_retries - the number of retries to establish the connection (default: unlimited)"},"1966":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-19","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"reconnection_interval - the interval between the reconnection attempts (default: 1s)"},"1967":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-20","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"reestablish_after - the time to wait before reestablishing the connection (default: 5s)"},"1968":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-21","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"heartbeat_interval - the interval between the heartbeat messages (default: 5s)"},"1969":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-22","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"nodelay - whether to use the TCP_NODELAY option or not (default: false)"},"1970":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-23","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"For QUIC, the connection string is parsed with the following options:"},"1971":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-24","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"response_buffer_size - the size of the response buffer (default: 10_000_000)"},"1972":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-25","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"max_concurrent_bidi_streams - the maximum number of concurrent bidirectional streams (default: 10000)"},"1973":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-26","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"datagram_send_buffer_size - the size of the datagram send buffer (default: 100_000)"},"1974":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-27","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"initial_mtu - the initial MTU size (default: 1200)"},"1975":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-28","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"send_window - the size of the send window (default: 100_000)"},"1976":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-29","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"receive_window - the size of the receive window (default: 100_000)"},"1977":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-30","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"keep_alive_interval - the interval between the keep-alive messages (default: 5000)"},"1978":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-31","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"max_idle_timeout - the maximum idle timeout (default: 10000)"},"1979":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-32","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"validate_certificate - whether to validate the server certificate or not (default: false)"},"1980":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-33","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"reconnection_retries - the number of retries to establish the connection (default: unlimited)"},"1981":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-34","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"reconnection_interval - the interval between the reconnection attempts (default: 1s)"},"1982":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-35","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"reestablish_after - the time to wait before reestablishing the connection (default: 5s)"},"1983":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-36","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"heartbeat_interval - the interval between the heartbeat messages (default: 5s)"},"1984":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-37","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"Unless you need to provide a specific implementation of the client-side Encryptor, Partitioner or adjust some other settings, you should be good to go with the connection string. On the other hand, you can always make use of IggyClientBuilder::from_connection_string() to extend the options on top of the provided connection string."},"1985":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-38","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"Additionally, if you were to check the internal implementation of IggyClient, you'd notice that it does use IggySharedMut<> which means that you can use a single instance of the client across multiple threads. Typically, it's a good idea to create a separate connection for producing and consuming, but it's not a requirement."},"1986":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-39","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#producer","content":"The producer is a high-level abstraction that allows you to send messages to the topic. It's quite simple to use and doesn't require you to handle the offsets, partitions or any other low-level details. To begin with, you can simply invoke client.producer() to get the IggyProducerBuilder allowing you to configure the producer. Let's take a look at the basic example:"},"1987":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-40","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#producer","content":"The code above will result in creating the producer that will try to send the messages in batches of 1000 every 5 milliseconds. You can choose between the direct (an instant producer) or the background (which will send the messages in the background by buffering them). The partitioning is set to balanced which means that the producer will try to distribute the messages evenly across all the partitions. The init() method is used to ensure that the producer is ready to send the messages by validating the existence of the stream, topic etc."},"1988":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-41","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#producer","content":"Finally, you can use the send() method to send the messages to the topic. The producer doesn't need to be a mutable reference, as it's only required during the initialization phase. Here's how you can send the messages:"},"1989":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-42","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#producer","content":"Of course, you can provide the message headers, custom binary serialization etc. as it's the same Message struct as the one used in the low-level API. The producer will take care of the rest, including the retries, partitioning, batching etc."},"1990":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-43","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#consumer","content":"The consumer is a high-level abstraction that allows you to receive the messages from the topic. It's quite simple to use and doesn't require you to handle the offsets, partitions or any other low-level details. To begin with, you can simply invoke client.consumer() to get the IggyConsumerBuilder allowing you to configure the consumer. Let's take a look at the basic example:"},"1991":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-44","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#consumer","content":"The code above will result in creating the consumer that will try to consume the messages in batches of 1000 every 1 millisecond. The auto-commit is set to commit the offset every second or when all the messages are consumed (fetched). The polling strategy is set to next which means that the consumer will try to consume the next available message from the partition currently assigned to the consumer group (you can also invoke a regular consumer() builder if you do not plan to use the consumer groups). The build() method is used to create the consumer."},"1992":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-45","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#consumer","content":"Finally, you can use the next() method to receive the messages from the topic. The consumer doesn't need to be a mutable reference, as it's only required during the initialization phase. The init() is used to ensure that the consumer is ready to receive the messages by validating the existence of the stream, topic, consumer group etc.  Here's how you can consume the messages:"},"1993":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-46","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#consumer","content":"In order to use the async iterator extension, add futures-util dependency."},"1994":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro","type":"page","content":"Intro","breadcrumbs":["Documentation","SDK","Rust"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro"},"1995":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro-0","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro#high-level-vs-low-level-api","content":"High-level vs low-level API"},"1996":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro-1","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro#connection-string","content":"Connection string"},"1997":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro-2","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro#quick-example","content":"Quick example"},"1998":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro-3","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro","content":"The Rust SDK is the primary and most feature-complete client for Iggy. It is available on crates.io and the source code is part of the core repository."},"1999":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro-4","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro#high-level-vs-low-level-api","content":"The SDK provides two layers:"},"2000":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro-5","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro#high-level-vs-low-level-api","content":"High-level API (recommended) - the easiest way to get started. It handles connection management, auto-batching, consumer group lifecycle, offset commits, retry logic, and reconnection out of the box. Use IggyClient, IggyProducer, and IggyConsumer for the best developer experience."},"2001":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro-6","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro#high-level-vs-low-level-api","content":"Low-level API - direct access to individual protocol operations. Useful when you need fine-grained control over every request, or when building custom abstractions on top."},"2002":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro-7","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro#high-level-vs-low-level-api","content":"The high-level API is built on top of the low-level one, so you can always drop down when needed."},"2003":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro-8","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro#connection-string","content":"The connection string is the simplest way to configure the client. It supports all four transport protocols:"},"2004":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro-9","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro#connection-string","content":"Options can be appended as query parameters:"},"2005":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro-10","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro#connection-string","content":"Personal Access Tokens are also supported:"},"2006":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro-11","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro#quick-example","content":"For the full getting started tutorial, see Getting Started. For the high-level producer/consumer builders, see High-level SDK and Stream Builder."},"2007":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","type":"page","content":"Stream Builder","breadcrumbs":["Documentation","SDK","Rust"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder"},"2008":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-0","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#iggystream-builder","content":"IggyStream Builder"},"2009":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-1","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#iggystreamproducer-builder","content":"IggyStreamProducer Builder"},"2010":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-2","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#producer-configuration","content":"Producer configuration"},"2011":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-3","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#iggystreamconsumer-builder","content":"IggyStreamConsumer Builder"},"2012":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-4","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#build-consumer-and-client","content":"Build consumer and client"},"2013":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-5","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#build-consumer-from-an-existing-client","content":"Build consumer from an existing client"},"2014":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-6","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#consumer-configuration","content":"Consumer configuration"},"2015":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-7","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","type":