stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","content":"The stream builder provides a convenient way to create the iggy client, producer and consumer for these use cases.\nAll source code examples are located in the examples folder of the iggy repository. Also,\nif you encounter a problem with any of the examples below, please ask in the community discord."},"2024":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-16","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#iggystream-builder","content":"In the first case, the IggyStream Builder offers a fast and efficient way to get you started:"},"2025":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-17","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#iggystream-builder","content":"As you can see, the IggyStream builder is used to create the iggy client, producer and consumer.\nHere, we use the default configuration to get started quickly, but you can always customize the configuration to fit\nyour requirements."},"2026":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-18","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#iggystream-builder","content":"The consume_messages method is not part of the IggyConsumer; instead, you import the IggyConsumerMessageExt\ntrait which provides the consume_messages method. The PrintEventConsumer implements the MessageConsumer trait\nand is invoked to process each incoming message. A simple implementation is show below:"},"2027":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-19","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#iggystreamproducer-builder","content":"When you implement the producer side, you can use the IggyStreamProducer to get started:"},"2028":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-20","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#iggystreamproducer-builder","content":"If you already have a custom iggy client, you can use that one by replacing the with_client_from_url\nconstructor with the following:"},"2029":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-21","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#iggystreamproducer-builder","content":"You find sample utils to build a customized iggy client in\nthe examples folder of the iggy\nrepository."},"2030":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-22","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#producer-configuration","content":"The IggyProducerConfig gives you a way to configure the producer in sufficient detail. Please note, if you have\nquestions about any of those settings, please ask in the community discord. For basic customization, the from_stream_topic constructor\nlets you set a custom stream and topic name as well as the maximum batch size and message send interval."},"2031":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-23","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#producer-configuration","content":"The remaining configuration fields are set to default values applicable to the most common use case. This should be sufficient for a simple application, or proof of concept without getting lost in details.\nHowever, for more complex applications, you might want to configure more\ndetails and for that, see below a commented example of the full producer configuration:"},"2032":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-24","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#producer-configuration","content":"Note, when your requirements exceed this configuration, you can still\nuse the underlying low level SDK for fine grained control over every detail of the producer."},"2033":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-25","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#iggystreamconsumer-builder","content":"When you have an existing server with multiple producers, you may have to implement a consumer for a specific stream or\ntopic. In some cases you may already have a configured iggy client, in others you may need to create\none. In either case, you can use the IggyStreamConsumer to create the consumer."},"2034":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-26","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#build-consumer-and-client","content":"Similar to the previous StreamBuilder, the IggyConsumerMessageExt is used to process messages using\nthe PrintEventConsumer implementation of the MessageConsumer trait."},"2035":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-27","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#build-consumer-from-an-existing-client","content":"In the event that you have an existing iggy client, you can use the IggyStreamConsumer::build method to create the\nconsumer. To do so, just replace the with_client_from_url with the following:"},"2036":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-28","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#build-consumer-from-an-existing-client","content":"Notice, you find some utils to build a customized iggy client in\nthe examples folder of the iggy\nrepository."},"2037":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-29","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#consumer-configuration","content":"The default configuration only exists to get you started quickly i.e. to test out an idea, draft an proof of concept or\nsimilar. In practice, you often want fine grained control over the configuration. The IggyConsumerConfig gives you a way\nto configure the consumer in sufficient detail without distracting with low level details.\nPlease note, if you have questions about any of those settings, please ask in\nthe community discord. See below a commented configuration example:"},"2038":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-30","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#add-consumers-dynamically-at-runtime","content":"When you create consumers on demand at application runtime, you have to\nensure that the stream and topic exist before creating the consumer and\nyou have to set the init_retries and init_interval in the stream builder\nto ensure the consumer retries a few more times in case the topic and stream are not immediately available."},"2039":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-31","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#add-consumers-dynamically-at-runtime","content":"However, when you cannot guarantee that the stream or topic exist before the consumer starts,\nyou have to set create_stream_if_not_exists and create_topic_if_not_exists to true in the IggyConsumerConfig\nto ensure the consumer creates them and starts correctly. Other than that, you just call the\nIggyStreamConsumer::build method as before i.e.:"},"2040":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-32","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#add-consumers-dynamically-at-runtime","content":"Where get_my_custom_iggy_consumer_config refers to a function that returns an IggyConsumerConfig\nthat specifies the stream and topic to consume as well the init retry or whether to create the stream and topic."},"2041":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-33","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#add-producers-dynamically-at-runtime","content":"Adding new producers to the iggy server at runtime is as simple as creating a new config and\ncalling the IggyStreamProducer::build method. Unlike the consumer, the producer always crates\nmissing streams or topics by default. The IggyConsumerConfig has a convenient builder to create\na new configuration from just the stream, topic, batch size and send interval. See the example below."},"2042":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-34","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#add-producers-dynamically-at-runtime","content":"If you encounter a problem with any of the examples show on this page,\nplease ask in the community discord."},"2043":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sources/elasticsearch","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sources/elasticsearch","type":"page","content":"Elasticsearch Source","breadcrumbs":["Documentation","Connectors","Sources"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/connectors/sources/elasticsearch"},"2044":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sources/elasticsearch-0","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sources/elasticsearch","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/connectors/sources/elasticsearch#features","content":"Features"},"2045":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sources/elasticsearch-1","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sources/elasticsearch","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/connectors/sources/elasticsearch#configuration","content":"Configuration"},"2046":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sources/elasticsearch-2","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sources/elasticsearch","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/connectors/sources/elasticsearch#basic-configuration","content":"Basic Configuration"},"2047":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sources/elasticsearch-3","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sources/elasticsearch","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/connectors/sources/elasticsearch#state-management-configuration","content":"State Management Configuration"},"2048":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sources/elasticsearch-4","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sources/elasticsearch","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/connectors/sources/elasticsearch#state-information","content":"State Information"},"2049":{"id